Muahmmara is a dip made with walnuts, chillis and roasted bell peppers. The wonderful thing
about making your own is that you can tailor the spice level to suit however hot your household
can handle!

Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Halve the @aubergine{1} lengthways. Score a diamond pattern into the flesh of each half, taking
care not to cut too deeply.

Place a #pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Place the aubergine skin-side down in the pan and fry for ~{2%minutes}. Lower the heat, turn
the aubergine over and cook for another ~{5%minutes}.

Halve the @bell pepper{1} lengthways. Deseed and slice into strips.

== Roasted Aubergine ==

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{} mix @oil{1/2%tbsp} (double for 4p) with half the
@Middle Eastern style spice mix{2%sachets}.

Place the aubergine skin-side down on a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle with the spiced oil.

Place the pepper and @garlic{2%cloves} on the baking tray alongside the aubergine.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Roast on the top shelf of the oven until tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Once cooked, remove from
the oven and cover to keep warm.

== Bulgur Wheat ==

Meanwhile, pour @water{240%ml} (double for 4p) into a #pot{}, stir in the
@vegetable stock{2%sachets} and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g}, bring back to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}.

Pop a #lid{} on the pot and remove from the heat.

Leave aside for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

> If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

== Preparation ==

Deseed the @chilli{1} and finely chop.

Zest and chop the @lemon{1} into thick wedges.

Roughly chop the @parsley{5%g} (stalks and all).

Squeeze the garlic from its skin.

Pop the @flatbread{2} into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

== Muhammara ==

Add the @walnuts{20%g}, garlic, chilli (use less if you don't like spice) and half the bell
pepper to a #blender{} or #food processor{}.

Add @oil{1/2%tbsp}, @sugar{1%tsp} (double both for 4p) and remaining Middle Eastern spice.

Puree until the consistency is that of a thick, smooth paste.

Squeeze in the juice of half the lemon wedges.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

== Assembly ==

Mix the remaining bell pepper through the bulgur, along with the parsley and lemon zest,
fluffing it up as you go.

Divide the bulgur between deep plates or bowls and top with the roasted aubergine.

Serve the homemade muhammara and warm flatbread on the side.

Garnish with remaining lemon wedges and a drizzle of @yoghurt{75%g}.